subject: p755328
stimulus:
Welcome to the experiment!

In this experiment, we are interested in how people learn the meanings of new words.

Imagine you are learning a brand new language. Someone tells you a new word for the first time. Can you figure out what the word means? In this experiment, you will be shown objects together with their names in a made-up language. Your job is to learn these new words.

Here's how the experiment will work. First, you will see a new word and examples of the word. Next, we will check your memory for this new word. Then, you will see objects which may or may not also match the new word. You will get a chance to choose one of these objects and learn its name. Finally, you will select all of the objects that you think match the new word. Remember, your job is to figure out what the new word means by learning which objects match the new word and which objects do NOT match the new word.

This process will repeat, with a brand new word. You will learn six words total following these steps. Do your best to figure out what each word means. The top 50 participants (out of 200) who do the best at identifying the meanings of new words will receive a $0.20 bonus in addition to the base compensation for the task.

Click Next to begin the experiment and learn the first word!
